http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: The Nebraska K-12 Physical Education Essential Learnings are intended to reflect what students should know and be able to do by the end of grades 2, 5, 8, and 12 as a result of participating in a quality physical education program. They are organized in grade level clusters of K-2, 3-5, 6-8, and 9-12, and they are composed of three overarching themes: Physical Education Literacy, Physical Activity and Fitness, and Responsible Physical Activity Behavior. Within each of these themes are two unique topic strands for a total of six topic strands. These strands are aligned to the National Standards for Physical Education and are articulated throughout the Physical Education Essential Learnings. The overarching themes and topic strands are identified to help organize the essential learnings. Within each strand are one or more essential learnings reflecting what students should know and be able to do at the end of each grade level range (e.g., K-2).
Physical Education Literacy
Skills
Demonstrate progress toward the mature form of locomotor and non-locomotor skills.
Demonstrate progress toward the mature form of selected manipulative skills.
Demonstrate progress toward the mature form of movement patterns and sequences.
Demonstrate the ability to adapt and adjust movement skills to uncomplicated, yet changing, environmental conditions and expectations.
Demonstrate mature forms of locomotor patterns and nonlocomotor skill combinations.
Demonstrate the mature forms of manipulative skills.
Demonstrate the ability to adapt and adjust a combination of movement skills in applied settings.
Demonstrate beginning skills of selected specialized movement forms.

Demonstrate competency in modified versions in at least one activity from three of the following categories: aquatics, dance, fitness activities, individual/dual sports, outdoor pursuits, self-defense, team sports, tumbling/gymnastics.

Demonstrate competency in basic and advanced skills and tactics in at least one activity from each of three of the following categories: aquatics, dance, fitness activities, individual/dual sports, outdoor pursuits, self-defense, and team sports.
Knowledge
Identify the critical elements of basic movements using movement vocabulary.
Apply feedback to improve performance.
Identify and apply principles of skill development to improve and enhance performance.
Demonstrate basic strategies in non-complex settings.
Explain principles of practice that enhance movement performance.
Define the critical elements of more advanced movement skills.
Identify and apply strategies and tactics within game play.
Explain biomechanical principles related to skill development.
Apply concepts and principles of human movement to the development of motor skills and the learning of new skills.
Analyze movement forms and apply proper strategies and tactics to a variety of physical activities.
Apply scientific and medical knowledge to aspects of exercise and injury prevention.
Physical Activity and Fitness
Active Lifestyle
Participate regularly in a wide variety of activities that involve locomotor, nonlocomotor and manipulative skills both inside and outside of physical education class.
Participate in physical activity in both school and non-school settings.
Set personal physical activity goals independently to meet needs and interests.
Participate regularly in physical activities in both school and non-school settings to accomplish personal activity goals.
Refine skills, expand knowledge, cultivate interest and strengthen desire to independently maintain an active lifestyle.
Fitness
Engage in moderate to vigorous physical activity.
Recognize the basic physiological indicators of physical activity.
Identify the basic components of health-related fitness.
Identify strengths and weaknesses based upon health-related fitness testing.
Engage in physical activities specifically related to each component of physical fitness.
Monitor physiological indicators that accompany moderate to vigorous physical activity and adjust activity accordingly.
Achieve desired levels of health-related fitness.
Utilize criterion-referenced standards of health-related fitness.
Explain principles of conditioning that enhance health-related fitness.
Achieve personal fitness based on criterion-referenced standards, taking into account variation in entry level and the long-term goal of achieving health-related fitness.
Demonstrate the skill and knowledge to create a fitness program based on personal needs.
Achieve desired levels of health-related fitness.
Physical Activity Behavior
Responsible Behavior
Demonstrate progress toward working cooperatively and interacting with other students regardless of differences.
Identify and model safety practices and class procedures.
Follow activity-specific safe practices, rules, procedures, and etiquette during physical activity.
Work individually and cooperatively to develop an awareness of and appreciation for individual differences.
Participate cooperatively in physical activity with persons of diverse characteristics and backgrounds.
Make responsible decisions to resolve and/or avoid conflicts.
Assist in establishing class rules related to safety practices and procedures.
Initiate responsible behavior, function independently and responsibly, and positively influence the behavior of others.
Develop and implement strategies in physical activity to promote inclusion of people of varying abilities and diverse cultural backgrounds.
Awareness
Express feelings about physical activities.
Attempt new activities.
Recognize physical activity as a positive opportunity for social development and group interaction.
Describe the physiological and psychological benefits that result from physical activity.
Attribute success and improvement to effort and practice.
Analyze the physical, emotional, and social benefits of physical activity.
Explore career/employment opportunities in fields related to physical activity.
Seek personally enjoyable and challenging experiences in physical activity opportunities.
Justify why participation in physical activity can be enjoyable and desirable.
Pursue lifetime physical activities that meet individual needs.
Investigate opportunities for employment related to physical activity.
